data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement — aborting a thread that exceeds a time limit.

**Problem:** `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. You must switch to cooperative cancellation.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // Task-based approach with CancellationToken for timeout
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must actually stop

The above detects the timeout but **the work keeps running in the background**. For true cooperative cancellation, accept a `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(token), token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token inside their work:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---------|-----------|
| Work continues after timeout if it doesn't check the token | Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at loop checkpoints |
| `CancellationTokenSource` not disposed → timer leak | Always wrap in `using` |
| Blocking calls (`Thread.Sleep`, synchronous I/O) ignore token | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter to distinguish timeout from external cancellation |
| Truly uncooperative code (can't modify to check token) | Move to a child **process** and use `Process.Kill()` — there's no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort` |

### What was removed

| Old API | Replacement |
|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` / `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Not needed — cancellation is cooperative, no forced exception to suppress |

The fundamental shift: the old code *forcibly injected* an exception into the thread. The new code *requests* cancellation — the work must voluntarily check and respond.
